<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-755-496  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 755 496.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  July 30 1990 v219 n5 p11(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Commerce, USTA join in cable plea. (Department of Commerce; USTelephone Association; telephone companies want to enter the cableTV business) (News of the Week)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mason, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Bush administration and the nation's telephone companies arepleading for action on Senate legislation that would allowtelephone companies to enter the cable TV business.andP;  According toa spokesman for the Department of Commerce, the administrationbelieves that consumer objectives can best be accomplished byexpanding competition in the provision of video services to thehome.andP;  Dean Swanson, representing the US Telephone Associationtells the Senate Communications subcommittee that telcocompetition would be good for cable TV consumers and thatcompetition would be essential for developing a broadband,fiber-based telecommunications infrastructure.andP;  Swanson says hecomes to Washington with 'a vision ...andP;  of a universally availablebroadband fiber optic public switched network.' Other witnesses,including representatives of the cable and newspaper industries,oppose telco entry into the cable marketplace.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone companiesUnited States. CongressDeregulationCable TVUnited States. Department of CommerceUnited States Telephone AssociationUnited States. Congress. Senate. Subcommittee on CommunicationsFiber OpticsCompetitionBroadbandGovernment RegulationIssues-SocietyMarket Entry.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Dean Swanson. (portrait)Person:    Swanson, Dean (telecommunication policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>